<HEADLINE>
<P>
REGIONAL ROUNDUP: DAMON TO SELL SUBSIDIARY TO PAY OFF BRIDGE LOAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Damon Corp. of Needham Heights, Mass., a subsidiary of American Magnetics Corp. 
in Sherman Oaks, said it agreed to sell one of Damon's subsidiaries -- 
International Equipment Co. 
</P>
<P>
-- for about $12 million to Life Sciences International PLC of the United 
Kingdom. 
</P>
<P>
Damon will use the proceeds of the sale to help pay off a $50-million bridge 
loan used in last spring's leveraged buyout of Damon by a group headed by 
American Magnetics and two of its top executives. 
</P>
<P>
The sale must be approved by Life Sciences' shareholders at a March 26 meeting 
and is expected to close by March 30. 
</P>
<P>
American Magnetics makes electronic readers for bank and credit cards. Damon 
runs a chain of medical testing laboratories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA031390-0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 188702 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 13, 1990, Tuesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 9B; Column 4 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
124 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
REGIONAL ROUNDUP: PERCEPTRONICS TO LAY OFF 50 AFTER LOSING CONTRACT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Perceptronics Inc. in Woodland Hills said it plans to lay off 50 workers in the 
next few months because it lost a defense contract. 
</P>
<P>
The company, which makes simulators and other training equipment, said it was 
not selected to provide continued support of SIMNET training sites. SIMNET, 
which Perceptronics helped develop, enables simulators of tanks, helicopters 
and other defense equipment to fight one another over a computer network. 
</P>
<P>
However, Perceptronics said, it was awarded a separate, $1.7-million contract 
to provide battle-training simulators to the Taiwanese army. The 1-year 
contract, Perceptronics' first with Taiwan, calls for the company to install a 
system that trains commanders in simulated battlefield situations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
