<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
NEW JERSEY; 
</P>
<P>
FLORIO SIGNS AUTO INSURANCE RATE BILL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gov. James J. Florio signed into law a bill to lower New Jersey's car insurance 
rates by 20%. 
</P>
<P>
Allstate Insurance Co. Vice President Edward Young said the firm would file 
suit within 30 days on the grounds that the law violates constitutional 
protections of due process. New Jersey's insurance rates average $1,000 a year. 
The bill eliminates the Joint Underwriting Assn., a state-operated pool for 
high-risk drivers that has a $3.1-billion debt. A $222 per car annual tab to 
keep the pool from bankruptcy will be dropped. The law requires the insurance 
industry to pay $1.4 billion of the pool's debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
AUTOMOBILE INSURANCE; INSURANCE INDUSTRY -- NEW JERSEY; NEW JERSEY -- SUITS; 
INSURANCE RATES; NEW JERSEY -- LAWS; DUE PROCESS OF LAW; ALLSTATE INSURANCE CO 
</P>
