<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHOWERS, HAIL AND SNOW FALL ON COUNTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DARRELL DAWSEY, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Scattered rain, hail and snow peppered a wide area of the Southland on Monday 
afternoon as a slow-moving storm system moved through the region. 
</P>
<P>
The showers were steady and relatively light in Orange County, although several 
Irvine residents reported that hail pelted the city for about 30 minutes at 
about 5 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
Malinee Churanakoses, 16, said she was hit by hail as she left a friend's house 
on Lindstrom Street. "It was thundering down rocks," said Churanakoses, who 
moved to Irvine with her parents four years ago. "It was very surprising. I 
thought I was back in Seattle." 
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the county, snow dusted the Santiago and Modjeska peaks in the 
Santa Ana Mountains. And a water spout -- which occurs when a tornado-like 
column of air passes over water -- was reported near Dana Point just before 
5:30 p.m. and dissipated about 10 minutes later, the National Weather Service 
said. 
</P>
<P>
Parts of the San Bernardino Mountains recorded up to 10 inches of snow in a 
matter of hours, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
Light snow also fell in the Grapevine area on Interstate 5 and on California 14 
in the Antelope Valley and a dusting could be seen on the San Gabriel Mountains 
from the Civic Center. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to snow, the system dumped short-lived rain and hail showers over 
the Southern California foothills and valleys. Rain also was reported in 
downtown Los Angeles, Long Beach and Santa Ana. 
</P>
<P>
While the length and severity of the rainfall varied, forecasters predicted as 
much as half an inch of rain in the heavier showers, along with the possibility 
of hail and gusty winds to 40 m.p.h. 
</P>
<P>
The weather created serious traffic problems in some areas. The Simi Valley 
Freeway was closed for more than three hours after a tractor trailer carrying 
tile overturned on wet pavement about 2:45 p.m. One person was injured. 
</P>
<P>
"Traffic is just screwed up all over on every one of our freeways," said 
California Highway Patrol spokesman Jim Wills. "The accident rate is higher 
than normal." 
</P>
<P>
Agriculture officials canceled Monday night's malathion spraying over 47 square 
miles of the San Fernando Valley because of the rain. 
</P>
<P>
Agriculture officials in Orange County expressed delight about the rainfall. 
Orange County Agriculture Commissioner James D. Harnett welcomed the showers, 
saying that the county's farmers "need every drop of rain they can get." 
</P>
<P>
"The rain may make it a nuisance for people who are harvesting their crops now 
but by and large the benefits of rain overshadow the negative points," Harnett 
said. "There is no substitute for good rain. It does things that imported water 
cannot do." 
</P>
<P>
Meteorologist Rick Dittmann of WeatherData Inc., however, said the showers 
would not significantly affect the prolonged drought being experienced in 
Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
Staff writer Davan Maharaj contributed to this report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
